default3default              defaultDisabled People &amp; the defaultThreat of Eviction:default&#xa0;default3.1
default              
defaultScottish Government’s Analytical Services Division have estimated
default the likely consequences of the introduction of the Under-Occupation Penalty. 
defaultThey estimated that 
default8,000 o
defaultf the households affected would move to smaller properties and thus manage to avoid the penalty whilst 
defaulthalf of th
defaulte remainder (43,000)
default would be able to maintain their rent payments
default and around half would fall into arrears
default.  
default&#xa0;
default3.2
default              
defaultOf the half that fell into a
defaultrrears they believed that a quarter (i.e. nearly 11,000 households) would eventually be evicted. Given that 79% of the households affected contain at least one disabled person that might mean 8,000+ disabled people being evicted and becoming homeless.
default&#xa0;
default3.3
default              
defaultInclusion Scotland believe that these
default 
defaultnow look to be
default over-optimistic projection
defaults given the levels of arrears in some 
defaultScottish 
defaultauthorities 
defaultis 
defaultalready at or above this level after only 4 months. 
default 
defaultHowever
default the additional 
default£20 million in 
defaultfunding being made avai
defaultlable 
defaultby Scottish Government 
defaultto Local Authorities to bolster DHP Budgets 
defaultshould
default have an impact in reducing 
defaultthe rate at which tenants are falling into arrears and thus being evicted.
default&#xa0;
default3.4
default              
defaultNevertheless Inclusion Scotland believes that disabled people will be
default amongst those least able to continue to meet their rent payments.  This is because the Under-Occupation Penalty has not been introduced in a vacuum but in a context where other benefits paid to sick and disabled people are being cut. Thus the cumulative i
defaultmpact of other welfare reforms will have an impact on their financial resilience and therefore their ability to meet increased rent payments.
default&#xa0;
default3.5
default              
defaultAccording to the Sheffield Hallam University research
default approximately 100,000 
defaultScots 
defaultdisabled people will be moved off Employment Support Allowance (ESA) 
defaultby 2015 
defaulteither because they exhaust their entitlement to contributory ESA or because they are re-classified as fully fit for work after a Work Capability Assessment (WCA). 
default&#xa0;
default3.6
default              
defaultGiven th
defaulte planned 20% budget reduction which the DWP is planning to achieve there will also be significant numbers (thousands at least) of disabled people on the Mobility Components and Care elements of DLA who will have to lose entitlement to the PIP to make the 
defaultnecessary savings.
default 
default&#xa0;
