default              
defaultResearch carried out by Demos on behalf of Scope
default confirms that a substantial proportion of disabled people will experience multiple cuts in their entitlement to benefits. The research suggests that across the UK 120,000 disabled people 
defaultwill experience at least a triple loss of benefits by 2018 with 99,000 experiencing a quadruple cut. 
defaultThe personal benefit 
defaultlosses will range from 
defaulta minimum of 
default£6,300 
defaultto 
default£23,461 
defaultper person by 2017.
default 
default&#xa0;
default3.13
default              
defaultResearch by the Scottish Public Health Observatory
default shows that 72,660 people were in receipt of three key benefits (Income Support/Pension Credit, Incapacity Benefit/Employment and Support Allowance/Severe Disablement Allowance, and Disability Living Allowance)
default affected by cuts
default, and 226,520 were in receipt
default of at least two of the key benefits.
default&#xa0;
default3.14
default      
defaultThus we think it safe to conclude that many of those losing ESA and/or other disability benefits (e.g. via the introduction of PIP
default and changes to ESA entitlement
default) will 
defaultalso be penalis
defaulted
default under the Under-Occupation regulations.  This means that they will already or in the future suffer substantial losses to their household incomes making it more likely that they will be unable to maintain 
defaulttheir 
