defaultentually be evicted.
default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default4default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultExemptionsdefault to the Under Occupation Ruledefault&#xa0;default4.1
default              
defaultInclusion Scotland believes that current exemptions to the Under Occupation rule are inconsistent with established case law, wider equality law and disabled people’s human rights. They are
default also being inconsistently applied by local authorities and Registered Social Landlords.
default&#xa0;
default4.2
default              
defaultSince the Court of Appeal judgment in 
defaultGorry V Department of Work and Pensions
default local authorities 
defaulthave received guidance from the DWP to allow an extra bedroom for 
defaultchildren who are unable to share because of their severe disabilities.
default  
defaultHowever no such exemption has been put in place for adult partners unable, or unwilling, to share a bed because of one
default,
default or both
default’
defaults
default,
default severe impairments.
default 
default&#xa0;
default4.
default3
default              
defaultWe believe that this failure to exempt couple’s unable to share a bed is inconsistent with established case law, with equalities law which states that disabled people should not be treated less favourably than non-disabled people  (as it could result in di
defaultsabled people’s health and safety being jeopardised) and with disabled people’s right, under the Human Rights Act and Article 8 of the European Convention, to a ‘home and family life’.   
default&#xa0;
default4.4     Inclusion Scotland
default believe that it is a totally unwarranted
default intrusion into the private lives of disabled people, and their partners, for the state to insist that they sleep in the same bed on pain of suffering a reduction to their housing benefit and that an exemption should be granted on these grounds forthwith.
default&#xa0;
default4.5
default 
default              
defaultInclusion Scotland also believes that an exemption should exist for sick and disabled people who use one of their rooms to store equipment or other items associated with supporting them to live with their condition or impairment. For example a room u
defaultsed to store a kidney dialysis machine is patently not being used as a bedroom and should not therefore be treated as one. 
default 
defaultA case (Lall v Westminster Council) on this very same  legal point was decided in favour of the claimant by a Lower Tier Tribunal ju
defaultdge. See here for details – 
defaulthttp://www.theguardian.com/society/2013/sep/26/bedroom-tax-westminster-council-defeat
default 
default&#xa0;
default4.6
default              
defaultW
defaulte view the failure to provide such an exemption as jeopardising sick and disabled people’s health and ability to live independently. As only disabled people have an essential need for additional rooms
default (that
default is not shared by non-disabled people
default)
default we believe
default 
defaultthat the Under-occupation penalty is
default 
defaulta breach of equality law which prohibits being treated differently on the grounds of disability
default and of Article 14 of the ECHR
default.
default 
defaultThis was also the view of a Lower Tier Tribunal judge in Glasgow in an as yet unreported 
defaultdec
defaultision -
default see here for the judge’
defaults comments: 
defaulthttp://govanlc.blogspot.co.uk/2013/10/european-convention-of-human-rights.html
default 
default&#xa0;
default4.7
default 
default              
defaultThere have also been a number of
default rulings in a Fife Lower Tier Tribunal on whether rooms can be treated as “bedrooms” for Under-occupation penalty purposes.  The judge in these cases ruled that rooms under 70 sq. feet in area could not be treated as bedrooms
default for use by adults and
default that exempt accommodation
default,
default where care and support was being provided by a Housing Association
default, whether or not contracted to do so by a local authority, 
defaultcoul
defaultd not be subjected to a penalty. See here for details – 
defaulthttp://www.insidehousing.co.uk/regulation/full-details-of-first-bedroom-tax-tribunal-rulings/6528701.article
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default5default              defaultDiscretionary Housing Paymentsdefault default&amp; DLA/PIP Entitlementdefault&#xa0;default5.1
default              
defaultTh
defaulte DWP made significant additional amounts of funding available to local authorities 
defaultto make Discretionary Housing Payments (DHPs) available to those affected by the Under Occupation penalty and other changes to Housing Benefit/Local Housing Allowance. 
default&#xa0;
default5.2
default              
defaultThe Guidance
default issued by the DWP specifically recognized that disabled people were likely to be disproportionately affected by the penalty and that local authorities should therefore consider making DHPs where, for example, “additional” bedrooms were being used by partn
defaulters who could not share a bed with a disabled spouse.
default&#xa0;
default5.3
default              
defaultHowever it appears that disabled people have been placed in a “Catch 22” situation in regards to being granted a DHP by local authorities. On the one hand they have to prove that they are a disable
defaultd person, in which case the local authority may ask for proof of entitlement to DLA or PIP.  But on the other when they prove said entitlement they are then told that they are not eligible for a DHP because they have additional funding that they can draw o
defaultn to pay the Under Occupation penalty, namely the very same DLA or PIP benefits payments!
default5.4
default              
defaultIt should be pointed out that DLA is paid to disabled people to assist in meeting the additional costs associated with their disability. If it is already being us
defaulted for that purpose then it should surely not be counted by local authorities as disposable income available to the disabled person to meet the Under Occupation penalty. Yet that is exactly what has been happening.  
default&#xa0;
default5.5
default              
defaultThere does not seem to be a consis
defaulttent approach across local authorities to a claimant having entitlement to DLA/PIP and their subsequent application for a DHP. The result is that severely impaired people having difficulty in paying their rent
default              
defaultare being denied support from the very funds s
defaultet aside for that purpose.  This will inevitably result in severe financial pressure on households containing a disabled person who 
defaultare 
defaultaffected by the ‘Bedroom Tax’, the very likely accumulation of rent arrears and the potential for, and reality, of evict
defaultions at some stage.   Needless to say the emotional stress that will be suffered by individuals and families will also be severe and has already led to incidents of suicide and self-harm.
default&#xa0;
default5.6 
default              
defaultInclusion Scotland believe that in taking DLA into account as 
defaultdisposable income for DHP purposes that local authorities are discriminating against disabled people as non-disabled people do not have access to DLA/PIP and are thus more likely to qualify for DHPs. 
default&#xa0;
default5.7
default              
defaultThis same legal argument was advanced by a disable
defaultd claimant in Glasgow and we note that the local authority then reviewed their DHP decision
default (see here for details - 
defaulthttp://disabilityrightsuk.org/news/2013
default/june/discretionary-housing-payment-includes-dla
default)
default&#xa0;
default5.8
default              
defaultHowever it is massively unfair that other disabled people within the same local authority area (and 
defaultalso in other authorities
default) may still be being denied DHPs on the grounds that they are receiving 
defaultDLA/PIP as no case law precedent was established that DLA should not be taken into account. This should be addressed by making DWP Guidance much more specific in calling for DLA/PIP payments to be disregarded by local authorities when considering whether t
defaulto award DHPs.
